<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Zigbee Is Used for Garden Sensors</h2>

  <p>
    Zigbee devices use low power and can form mesh networks, extending range through repeaters.
  </p>

  <p>
    This allows:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>long battery life</li>
    <li>integration with smart systems</li>
    <li>flexible network expansion</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    But outdoor use introduces new challenges.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Outdoor Limitations Most People Miss</h2>

  <p>
    Zigbee networks rely on nearby devices to relay signals. Outdoors, you often lose that mesh support.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>fewer repeaters in range</li>
    <li>walls and distance reduce signal strength</li>
    <li>weather exposure affects hardware reliability</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This makes placement critical.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Zigbee Soil Sensor</h2>

  <h3>Stable Connectivity</h3>
  <p>
    Maintains connection without frequent dropouts.
  </p>

  <h3>Outdoor Durability</h3>
  <p>
    Handles moisture, temperature changes, and soil conditions.
  </p>

  <h3>Consistent Readings</h3>
  <p>
    Reliable trends matter more than exact numbers.
  </p>

  <h3>Mesh Network Support</h3>
  <p>
    Works well with repeaters to extend range.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Placement Matters More Than the Sensor</h2>

  <p>
    Even a good sensor fails if placed outside reliable network range.
  </p>

  <p>
    To improve performance:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>position sensors within range of repeaters</li>
    <li>use Zigbee plugs or hubs to extend the mesh</li>
    <li>avoid placing sensors behind major obstacles</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Network design is part of the system.
  </p>
</section>

